results.name: a(n) is the number of pentanomials x^n + x^a + x^b + x^c + 1 that are irreducible over GF(2) for n > a > b > c > 0.
comment: Is is conjectured that a(n) > 0 for all n >= 4.
link: Jianing Song, Table of n, a(n) for n = 4..173
example: a(4) = 1 because there is only one irreducible pentanomial of degree 4 over GF(2), namely x^4 + x^3 + x^2 + x + 1.

a(6) = 4 because there are 4 irreducible pentanomials of degree 6 over GF(2): x^6 + x^4 + x^2 + x + 1, x^6 + x^4 + x^3 + x + 1, x^6 + x^5 + x^2 + x + 1, x^6 + x^5 + x^3 + x^2 + 1, x^6 + x^5 + x^4 + x + 1 and x^6 + x^5 + x^4 + x^2 + 1.
program: (PARI) a(n) = sum(a=3, n-1, sum(b=2, a-1, sum(c=1, b-1, polisirreducible(Mod(x^n+x^a+x^b+x^c+1, 2)))))
xref: Cf. A014580 (irreducible polynomials over GF(2) encoded as binary numbers), A057646.
